# Domain structure

Organize by **bounded context** (business language), not by technical layer.

## Packages

| Path | Responsibility |
|------|----------------|
| `packages/shared-kernel` (`@velon/shared`) | Permissions, plans, roles, nav, shared types only |
| `packages/database` (`@velon/database`) | Prisma schema, migrations, seed |
| `backend/src/{context}/` (`@velon/backend`) | Nest feature module per domain |
| `frontend/src/` (`@velon/frontend`) | Routes, domain components, domain API clients |

## Naming

- Backend files: `{context}` or `{context}-{aggregate}` prefix, role suffix last (`.service.ts`, `.controller.ts`, `.repositories.ts`, `.dto.ts`, `.spec.ts`).
- Frontend: domain UI in `components/{context}/`, helpers and API clients in `lib/{context}/`, routes stay URL-shaped. Shared HTTP client only in `lib/api/`.
- Frontend imports use `@/` absolute paths. Same-context backend imports use `./`; cross-context use `../other-context/`.

## Placement

- New tenant feature → backend module under `backend/src/<context>/`, shared permissions, frontend routes + `lib/{context}/` + `components/{context}/`, isolation tests.
- Platform-only → `platform/` + `/admin` routes, never mixed into tenant modules.
- No god `utils/` files; keep helpers next to their context (`lib/shared/` only for true cross-cutting UI helpers).

Use the `velon-domain-structure`, `domain-driven-design`, and `clean-ddd-hexagonal` skills when adding or moving modules.
